{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17514119","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17514119"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:18:40+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:18:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12275"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12275","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12275"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.26,0.1,0.18,0.35,0.12]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4797"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"99449"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4797","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4797"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12275"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"81835"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1184"},{"type":"tags","id":"1797"},{"type":"tags","id":"4625"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"10434"},{"type":"tags","id":"11340"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7699"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7732"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34090"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"99449","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/99449"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a few hours history of sudden onset involuntary movements of her right arm and visual disturbance. She has a medical history of hypertension and dyslipidaemia. Her medications include amlodipine and rosuvastatin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 88/min, blood pressure 162/98 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.0\u00b0C. Neurological examination reveals violent, irregular flinging movements of the right arm and right homonymous hemianopia.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following structures is most likely responsible for the abnormal movements?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Caudate nucleus","Cerebellum","Substantia nigra","Subthalamic nucleus","Thalamus"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with acute onset hemiballismus - characterised by violent, irregular flinging movements typically affecting proximal limbs. The concurrent homonymous hemianopia and vascular risk factors suggest an acute posterior circulation stroke affecting both the subthalamic nucleus and occipital cortex.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Esubthalamic nucleus\u003C/strong\u003E normally provides inhibitory input to the globus pallidus. When damaged, this leads to decreased pallidal inhibition of the thalamus, resulting in the characteristic flinging movements of hemiballismus. The posterior cerebral artery supplies both the subthalamic nucleus and the occipital lobe visual cortex.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe most common cause of hemiballismus is ischaemic or haemorrhagic stroke affecting the subthalamic nucleus. Other causes include space-occupying lesions (tumours, abscesses), demyelinating diseases (multiple sclerosis), traumatic brain injury, non-ketotic hyperglycaemia (particularly in people with diabetes), and infections (HIV-associated toxoplasmosis, tuberculosis).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ecaudate nucleus\u003C/strong\u003E is primarily involved in cognitive function, motivation, and emotion. Lesions typically cause behavioral changes and cognitive deficits rather than movement disorders.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ecerebellum\u003C/strong\u003E coordinates voluntary movement, balance, and posture. Cerebellar lesions cause ataxia, dysmetria, and intention tremor rather than ballistic movements.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Esubstantia nigra\u003C/strong\u003E is involved in movement control through dopaminergic pathways. Damage typically causes parkinsonian features including bradykinesia, rigidity, and resting tremor.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ethalamus\u003C/strong\u003E is a relay center for sensory and motor signals. Thalamic lesions can cause sensory deficits, pain syndromes, or movement disorders, but not typically hemiballismus.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Hemiballismus is characterised by violent, irregular flinging movements of proximal limbs due to contralateral subthalamic nucleus lesions.","Acute onset hemiballismus with homonymous hemianopia suggests posterior circulation stroke affecting the subthalamic nucleus and visual cortex.","The posterior cerebral artery supplies the subthalamic nucleus, occipital lobe, and inferior temporal lobe."],"references":["Hawley JS, Weiner WJ. Hemiballismus: Current concepts and review. Parkinsonism Relat Disord. 2012 Feb;18(2):125\u20139. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/21930415/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"81835"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12275"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"81835","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/81835"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-20T20:39:22+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-20T20:40:26+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4797"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"99449"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags",